North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continued sanctions deepened their distrust of the United States and that the country would certainly not unilaterally give up nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the General Assembly that North Korea has taken “marked measures of goodwill” in recent years, such as halting nuclear missile tests, dismantling its nuclear test base and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technologies.
“We have not received a similar response from the United States,” he said.
“Without any trust in the United States, we will not be able to rely on our national security, and under such circumstances, we will by no means be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While Ri has repeatedly heard complaints from North Korea about Washington's opposition to a phased approach to nuclear disarmament that would reward North Korea in stages of action, his statement stood out by the fact that he had not completely rejected the idea of a bilateral pact.
Ri pointed to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first meeting of the US President and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on “disarmament of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump promised to ensure North Korea’s security.
North Korea is aiming for a formal end to the 1950-1953 Korean war, but the United States says that Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington also refuses to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States demands nuclear disarmament first and increases the pressure of sanctions to achieve its goal by coercive methods, even by renouncing declarations of an end to the war,” Ri said.
“To think that we can be stalked by sanctions is the same thing as having utopian dreams for people we don’t care about.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader underscored at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister emphasized three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months: “If South Korea were the other country on the issue of nuclear disarmament, and not the US, the issue of nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula would not have been so acute.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech has changed dramatically compared to last year when he told the UN General Assembly that when “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile master” preparing a suicide mission, steering North Korea’s missiles into the U.S. was absolutely not.
Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea at the United Nations, lauded Kim for the courage to take steps towards disarmament, but said much still needed to be done and that sanctions must remain until the North's nuclear-defense demands are met.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timeline for it, saying that "if it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia said the UN Security Council should pay Pyongyang back for what it has done.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pomeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that "the Security Council's sanctions must be resolutely pursued without any concessions until a full and definitive, evidence-confirmed nuclear disarmament is carried out."
The Security Council has voted in favour of sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in order to prevent the financing of Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri in the backdrop of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to pave the way for the next meeting.
