Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University's health services department, said the university had decided to offer the course when it turned out that students were severely sleep-deprived during the week.
The hour-long course includes a series of interactive tasks.
One section contains a photo of the dormitory room where students can click on a cup of coffee, curtains, workouts and books to learn about the effects of caffeine, light, how sleep deprivation affects sports performance, and how important a walking sleep routine is.
In the next section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A student campus map with interactive icons that encourage participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We understand that this will not immediately change the behavior of the students.
